    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.14570v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        Despite their theoretical importance, dynamic Bayesian networks associated with quantum processes are currently not accessible experimentally. We here describe a general scheme to determine the multi-time path probability of a Bayesian network based on local measurements on independent copies of a composite quantum system combined with postselection. We further show that this protocol corresponds&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.14570v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.14570v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.14570v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        Despite their theoretical importance, dynamic Bayesian networks associated with quantum processes are currently not accessible experimentally. We here describe a general scheme to determine the multi-time path probability of a Bayesian network based on local measurements on independent copies of a composite quantum system combined with postselection. We further show that this protocol corresponds to a non-projective measurement. It thus allows the investigation of the multi-time properties of a given local observable while fully preserving all its quantum features.
