    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Casimir Interaction Between a Plane and a Sphere: Correction to the Proximity-Force Approximation at Intermediate Temperatures
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Henning%2C+V">Vinicius Henning</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Spreng%2C+B">Benjamin Spreng</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Neto%2C+P+A+M">Paulo A. Maia Neto</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Ingold%2C+G">Gert-Ludwig Ingold</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13927v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        We consider the Casimir interaction energy between a plane and a sphere of radius $R$ at finite temperature $T$ as a function of the distance of closest approach $L$. Typical experimental conditions are such that the thermal wavelength $λ_T=\hbar c/k_\mathrm{B}T$ satisfies the condition $L\ll λ_T\ll R$. We derive the leading correction to the proximity-force approximation valid for such intermedia&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13927v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.13927v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13927v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We consider the Casimir interaction energy between a plane and a sphere of radius $R$ at finite temperature $T$ as a function of the distance of closest approach $L$. Typical experimental conditions are such that the thermal wavelength $λ_T=\hbar c/k_\mathrm{B}T$ satisfies the condition $L\ll λ_T\ll R$. We derive the leading correction to the proximity-force approximation valid for such intermediate temperatures by developing the scattering formula in the plane-wave basis. Our analytical result captures the joint effect of the spherical geometry and temperature and is written as a sum of temperature-dependent logarithmic terms. Surprisingly, two of the logarithmic terms arise from the Matsubara zero-frequency contribution.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13927v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.13927v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 25 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="comments is-size-7">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Comments:</span>
      <span class="has-text-grey-dark mathjax">20 pages, 3 figures</span>
    </p>
    

    

    
