    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Vacuum polarization with zero-range potentials on a hyperplane
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Fermi%2C+D">Davide Fermi</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13720v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        The quantum vacuum fluctuations of a neutral scalar field induced by background zero-range potentials concentrated on a flat hyperplane of co-dimension $1$ in $(d+1)$-dimensional Minkowski spacetime are investigated. Perfectly reflecting and semitransparent surfaces are both taken into account, making reference to the most general local, homogeneous and isotropic boundary conditions compatible wit&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13720v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.13720v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13720v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        The quantum vacuum fluctuations of a neutral scalar field induced by background zero-range potentials concentrated on a flat hyperplane of co-dimension $1$ in $(d+1)$-dimensional Minkowski spacetime are investigated. Perfectly reflecting and semitransparent surfaces are both taken into account, making reference to the most general local, homogeneous and isotropic boundary conditions compatible with the unitarity of the quantum field theory. The renormalized vacuum polarization is computed for both zero and non-zero mass of the field, implementing a local version of the zeta regularization technique. The asymptotic behaviours of the vacuum polarization for small and large distances from the hyperplane are determined to leading order. It is shown that boundary divergences are soften in the specific case of a pure Dirac delta potential.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13720v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.13720v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 25 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
